Pattern: Silent centralization
The system presents as distributed while core controls quietly become consolidated.
Observed in: Governance heavy chains, validator governed systems, admin upgrade protocols.
Behavior: A few operators, multisigs, or infrastructure providers become the real control plane.
Risk impl: The protocol’s resilience is overstated because the single points of failure are hidden in plain sight.
Frequency: high

Pattern: Incentive capture spiral
Once one actor learns how to farm the system, others copy the pattern until the whole protocol degrades.
Observed in: Token incentive networks, reputation systems.
Behavior: Honest users either imitate the exploitative behavior or exit.
Risk impl: The protocol rewards the worst adaptation first and then normalizes it.
Frequency: high

Pattern: Governance theater
Governance continues to function as a public ritual after real decision making has already moved elsewhere.
Observed in: DAOs, token holder voting systems, foundation governed ecosystems.
Behavior: Votes happen, but outcomes are shaped by prior coordination, legal control, or off chain influence.
Risk impl: Stakeholders misprice their actual influence and underestimate capture risk.
Frequency: medium

Pattern: Recovery path collapse
When something fails, the protocol has no clean way to restore trust, liquidity, or operating continuity.
Observed in: Cross chain systems, agent execution networks.
Behavior: Incident response becomes ad hoc, slow, and politically contested.
Risk impl: The first failure becomes a confidence event, not just a technical event.
Frequency: medium

Pattern: Liveness dependency mismatch
An on-chain instrument depends on an off-chain execution path that has different availability guarantees.
Observed in: Derivatives platforms, limit order systems with backend matching layers.
Behavior: The financial instrument is permanent and on chain. Settlement, order matching, or exercise depends on a backend service that can go down. During volatile windows, exactly when users need to act, the execution path is most likely to be under stress. The instrument survives. The ability to use it does not.
Risk impl: Users hold assets they cannot act on when it matters most. The trust model of the protocol overstates the availability of the execution layer because the on chain component is conflated with the full system.
Frequency: high

Pattern: Cross-chain execution surface collapse
A single agent or key operates across multiple chains without a documented failure or recovery path for cross-chain state inconsistency.
Observed in: Multi chain agent protocols, cross chain oracle networks
Behavior: An agent submits oracle results on one chain and executes financial transactions on another using the same wallet. A compromise, nonce collision, or chain-specific failure on either side creates an inconsistent state that the protocol has no defined procedure to resolve. Each chain sees a valid state locally. The combined state is broken.
Risk impl: Cross chain execution surfaces are treated as two separate operational concerns when they share a single trust anchor. Recovery requires manual intervention across chains simultaneously, with no documented runbook.
Frequency: medium
